	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade policy: Review of relevance of different trade agreements to Pacific Island Countries</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The United Nations University Institute on Comparative Regional Integration Studies has published an analysis of Pacific Islands trade negotiations, which argues that given the economic characteristics of the Pacific Islands Countries’ (PIC) intra-regional trade, agreements (especially PICTA and MSGTA, for example) could only make a limited contribution to the economic development objectives of the countries concerned. It sees such arrangements as ‘stepping stones to more ambitious … integration with the global economy’.</p><p>With regard to the EPA process, the paper argues that these negotiations were of ‘little immediate relevance’ to Pacific island countries other than Fiji and Papua New Guinea. It notes that efforts to ‘widen the scope of the EPA to deliver development-related benefits of greater consequence’ to other Pacific countries ‘have so far been largely unsuccessful’. It should be noted, however, that the negotiations for a comprehensive EPA to include the other Pacific ACP (PACP) member states have yet to be concluded.</p><p>The paper suggests that a wider agenda of issues also needs to be addressed in the PACER Plus process if ‘major development-related benefits’ are to be delivered to PICs. Both the EPA and PACER Plus are regarded not only as FTAs, but also as developmental tools for PICs. It argues that the focus on the EU, Australia and New Zealand has limited the attention paid to trade with the rapidly growing economies of East Asia, where ‘the PICs are facing progressively increasing discrimination’ following the conclusion of a multiplicity of trade agreements by governments of the East Asia region.</p><p>While PICs can look towards being integrated with East Asia in future, their current focus is still directed at maximising their gains from both EPA and PACER Plus. The former is yet to be concluded, while the latter has just been launched.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
United Nations University Institute on Comparative Regional Integration Studies, ‘South-south and north-south trade agreements: The Pacific Islands case’, by R. Scollay, UNU-CRIS working papers W-2010/7, 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Scollay_EN_81210_UNUCRIS_South-South%20and%20North-South%20Trade%20Agreements.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Scollay_EN_81210_UNUCRIS_South...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The case for paying greater attention to the potential of trade with East Asian economies within the overall development of Pacific trade relations would appear to be strong. For example, market analyst Czarnikow’s recent report on the prospects for global sugar markets up to 2030 projected that Asia’s share of global sugar consumption would increase from 40% in 2010 to 49% in 2030, while EU sugar consumption is ‘expected to remain stable over the next 20 years’. Clearly, in the sugar sector the focus of global consumption is shifting east. This is likely to be the case across a range of food and agricultural products, an area where Pacific countries could develop niche exports. In this context it should be noted that this consumption growth relates not only to ‘necessity purchase’ items – bulk commodities where price competitiveness is the key – but also to ‘luxury purchase’ products, where quality-based production is required. It is in these latter areas where potentially Pacific countries could develop niche markets, especially for products certified under fair-trade or organic labels. This is already the case for products as diverse as bottled water and skin-care products.</p><p>These new sectors are attracting increasing attention from both the private sector operators and non-state actors. The engagement of non-state actors tends to be greatly assisted through specifically targeted and strategic technical and development assistance.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
